04742nam a22007215i 9780813571348DE-B159720191221113333.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||191221s2014    nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97808135713487 a10.36019/97808135713482doi  a(DE-B1597)526265  a(OCoLC)1121054161  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 7aHIS0000002bisacsh1 aLevy, Teresita A., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut.10aPuerto Ricans in the Empire :bTobacco Growers and U.S. Colonialism /cTeresita A. Levy. 1aNew Brunswick, NJ : bRutgers University Press, c[2014] 4c©2015  a1 online resource (182 p.) :b6 figures, 33 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Figures -- tList of Tables -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. The Development of the Tobacco Economy in Puerto Rico -- t2. Life in the Tobacco Regions of Puerto Rico -- t3. Politics: Tobacco Growers and Agricultural Organizations -- t4. Law: The Extension of Federal Agricultural Credit Legislation to Puerto Rico -- t5. Technology: Modern Agriculture, Home Management, and Rural Progress -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tSelected Bibliography -- tIndex -- tAbout the Author0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aMost studies of Puerto Rico's relations with the United States have focused on the sugar industry, recounting a tale of victimization and imperial abuse driven by the interests of U.S. sugar companies. But inPuerto Ricans in the Empire, Teresita A. Levy looks at a different agricultural sector, tobacco growing, and tells a story in which Puerto Ricans challenged U.S. officials and fought successfully for legislation that benefited the island. Levy describes how small-scale, politically involved, independent landowners grew most of the tobacco in Puerto Rico. She shows how, to gain access to political power, tobacco farmers joined local agricultural leagues and the leading farmers' association, the Asociación de Agricultores Puertorriqueños (AAP). Through their affiliation with the AAP, they successfully lobbied U.S. administrators in San Juan and Washington, participated in government-sponsored agricultural programs, solicited agricultural credit from governmental sources, and sought scientific education in a variety of public programs, all to boost their share of the tobacco-leaf market in the United States. By their own efforts, Levy argues, Puerto Ricans demanded and won inclusion in the empire, in terms that were defined not only by the colonial power, but also by the colonized. The relationship between Puerto Rico and the United States was undoubtedly colonial in nature, but, as Puerto Ricans in the Empire shows, it was not unilateral. It was a dynamic, elastic, and ever-changing interaction, where Puerto Ricans actively participated in the economic and political processes of a negotiated empire.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Dez 2019) 0aTobacco industryzPuerto RicoxHistory. 0aTobaccoxPolitical aspectszPuerto RicoxHistory. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066331008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRUP eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311066615140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780813571348423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780813571348.jpg  a978-3-11-066331-0  RUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  a978-3-11-066615-1  RUP eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA14ALL  aPDA16SSH  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA1ALL  aPDA